intro: Gompholobium aristatum var. muticum, commonly known as the narrow-leafed gompholobium, is a flowering plant native to Australia. It belongs to the legume family, Fabaceae, and is characterized by its slender, often hairy stems and small, clustered flowers. The plant typically grows in sandy or rocky soils and is found in arid or semi-arid regions. Its leaves are narrow and often have a distinctive glandular appearance, contributing to its unique botanical identity.
